Introduction

The following will investigate the aplicabliity of different algorithm for the classfication of different types of dumbell excecises based on sensorial data collected by a test group carrying out the different excercises.

Loading Data

The training and test data are loaded from disk. Due to the large number of features, only features of the following kind will be retained: those no containing NA’s and those not consisting of feature variables with large numbers of “blank” values. Furthermore the timestamps, new_window, num_window, user_name and X features will be disregarded (the last one is particularly important to remove, as including it would allow any tree-based algorthim to trivially find a perfect split, with no predicitive power).

Finally the provided training data will be split into training and test data, whereas the provided test data will be considered the validation set. This is necessary, as, in order to asses the degree of overfitting, a test set with known classe variable is necessary (this is not the case for the data in pml-testing.csv).

pmlTrain <- read.csv("pml-training.csv")
pmlValidate <- read.csv("pml-testing.csv")

cols=colSums(is.na(pmlTrain))==0
pmlTrainClean <- pmlTrain[,cols]
pmlValidateClean <- pmlValidate[,cols]
cols=colSums(pmlTrainClean=="")==0
pmlTrainClean <- pmlTrainClean[,cols]
pmlValidateClean <- pmlValidateClean[,cols]
rmCols=c(1,2,3,4,5,6,7)
pmlTrainClean <- pmlTrainClean[,-rmCols]
pmlValidateClean <- pmlValidateClean[,-rmCols]

inTrain = createDataPartition(pmlTrainClean$classe, p = 0.7)[[1]]
training = pmlTrainClean[ inTrain, ]
testing = pmlTrainClean[ -inTrain, ]

Visual Inspection of Data

This preceeding analysis still leaves a large number of features to work with. As an attempt to reduce this we inspect visually how each remaing variable depends on the classe variable.

df <- gather(-classe,key="var",value="value",data=training)
p <- ggplot(data=df,aes(x=classe,color=classe,y=value))
p <- p + geom_boxplot()
p <- p + facet_wrap(~ var, scales = "free")
p

Evidently there are clear trends separating the classes in different variables, but a small subset of variables allowing for a reduced model is not ovious. Thus the subsequent analysis will proceed with all the features of the previous plot.

Computing Models

We will begin with a straightforward tree split.

fitRpart <- train(classe ~ .,data=training,method="rpart")
predTrain <- predict(fitRpart, training)
predTest <- predict(fitRpart, testing)
cmTrain <- confusionMatrix(predTrain, training$classe)
cmTest <- confusionMatrix(predTest, testing$classe)

Inspection of the confusion matrices (see below) shows an accuracy of around 49% each. This suggests that rpart does significantly better than chance and leads to little overfitting. That being said ~50% leaves room for improvment.

Next the data is trained with linear discriminant analysis (possbile as all non-continuous features have been removed) as an example of a type of analysis not relying on a tree approach.

fitLda <- train(classe ~ ., data=training, method="lda")
predTrainLda <- predict(fitLda, training)
predTestLda <- predict(fitLda, testing)
cmTrainLda <- confusionMatrix(predTrainLda, training$classe)
cmTestLda <- confusionMatrix(predTestLda, testing$classe)

The confusion matrices shown below demonstrate that we have now achieved an accuracy of around 70% in both test and training data. A significant improvment of the application of rpart.

However, the initial succes of rpart suggest that a more complex model based on trees might outperform LDA. As such we will use the “gbm” method (note that on my laptop running this code takes ~30 min and fails to run completely if run as part of knitr, so I only show the code below while not executing it. As such the resulting confusion matrices whill not be shown but rather only the result quoted):

set.seed(1234)
fitGbm <- train(classe ~ .,data=training,method="gbm")
predTrain <- predict(fitRpart, training)
predTest <- predict(fitRpart, testing)
cmTrain <- confusionMatrix(predTrain, training$classe)
cmTest <- confusionMatrix(predTest, testing$classe)

Evaluating once more the confusion matrix we see that now an accuracy greater than 90% is reached for the testing set. Furthermore the results produced for the validation set are 100% correct (submitting them to the course quiz).

cmTrain
cmTest

Conclusions

The above calculations have clearly shown that prediction based on the GBM method carried out over the selected features is highly succesful for the task at hand. One might wish to carry out a more careful analysis of weather the set of features can be reduced or if maybe the random forest method (RF) gives better results still, but given that I am operating with a 250€ laptop, this is very tiresome.
